title: For Sale/Trade:  BM 59
postcontent:
Want to trade my Santa Fe marked early M-59 in .308. This is NOT a re-welded receiver like the majority or the ensuing problems, it is before Beretta made them put the licensing stamp on them. Comes with 2 Beretta marked 20rd magazines. Beretta's version of the M1A / M14.
Will get pics to anyone interested and can answer any questions.

FTF local would be nice but can ship as needed to FFL.



It has a mid 40's Springfield Garand receiver they refinished, that again is not a reweld job that is unsafe to fire. Very few were made at the very beginning before they moved over to the much cheaper and plentiful cut up receivers that were so common. Is functionally identical to a semi-auto Beretta BM-59 except made in America. Every part is either Garand or BM-59 GI issue. Has the standard dings for an older rifle in the safe, only noticeable issues are looks like a shooter had a ring on his right hand while shooting that left some dings, and the crappy paint Beretta used on the ext of the gas tube is wearing. A Beretta import BM59 seem to be going for about 2500-3500 when available. This is an affordable alternative to own a cool piece of history in the m-14 family development.

We Buy Antiques-

We look for the finest antiques available in any category, including but not limited to: American and European antique furniture,folk art,oil paintings, prints, jewelry and silver (especially Georg Jensen, Tiffany and Cartier), ceramics (hard and soft paste porcelain, Staffordshire, redware, majolica, faience, Oriental), blown and cut glass, toys, tin and glass plate photographs, nautical items Louis Vuitton luggage. We are also seeking the following 20th century names: Stickley, Roycroft, Limberts, Frank Lloyd Wright, Nakashima, Eames, Herman Miller, Plycraft,Knoll,Hans Wegner, Rookwood, Fulper, Grueby, Teco, and Spratling.



Take CLEAR Digital Photographs- of all sides of the item along with close-ups of details, marks, signatures, and any damage or repairs. Provide measurements of the item, specific to details. For example, the height of the back of the chair, the length of the arms, the width of the seat,etc. Note the price that you wish to realize for your item. We do not make offers. We consider offers to be a form of appraisal which is a service that we charge for.
